662. Deoumam partem. It was a custom amongst the ancient Romans to devote a tenth part of their gains in trade, or of the spoils of war, to Hercules, the guardian-god of property; cp. Stich. 233, 3863 Truc. ii. 7, 123 Cic„ N. D. iii. 36, 88; Off. ii. 17, 58. The fact is also recorded in inscriptions, and attested by later writers, amongst whom Dionysius of Halicarnassus says that the custom was instituted by Hercules himself, at the altar erected to his honour by king Evander, near the Palatine hill.
